\section{Language}

We have various types of hypotheses in the context.
The pseudo-hypothesis $h$, with no variable name, tracks the single bit of information by its presence or absence
 of whether we have morally added a hyp of type $H$ yet. We
let the type $H$ internalize that. The presence of $h$ in the context isn't in any particular place.
Multiple copies of $h$ in the context automatically coalesce. The exploded context
 $\emptyset$ is  meant to be like a collapsed context with a $0$ hyp in it.

We don't have any variable constructors like $x[h]$ anymore.
\[\begin{tabular}{rccl}
  Contexts&$\Gamma$&$::=$&$\cdot \celse \emptyset \celse \Gamma, x : A \celse \Gamma, x :: A \celse \Gamma, x \div A\celse \Gamma, h$\\
  Types&$A$&$::=$&$\cdots \celse G_A M \celse \lax A \celse \blat A $\\
  Terms&$M$&$::=$&$\cdots \celse \{M\} \celse \pi_M N \celse \iblat M \celse \eblat M \celse \ilax M \celse \elax M $\\
\end{tabular}\]

\subsection{Operations}
\[\begin{tabular}{l}
If $\Gamma$ is a context, then $ \Gamma^\oplus$ is a context.\\
If $\Gamma$ is a context, then $\Gamma^\ominus$ is a context.\\
\end{tabular}\]

\[\begin{tabular}{rcl}
 $ (\Gamma, x : A)^\oplus$&$:=$&$(\Gamma^\oplus, x :: A)$\\
 $ (\Gamma, x :: A)^\oplus$&$:=$&$(\Gamma^\oplus, x :: A)$\\
 $ (\Gamma, x \div A)^\oplus$&$:=$&$(\Gamma^\oplus, x \div A)$\\
 $ (\Gamma, h)^\oplus$&$:=$&$\emptyset$\\
\end{tabular}\]

\[\begin{tabular}{rcl}
 $ (\Gamma, x : A)^\ominus$&$:=$&$(\Gamma^\ominus, x \div A)$\\
 $ (\Gamma, x :: A)^\ominus$&$:=$&$(\Gamma^\ominus, x :: A)$\\
 $ (\Gamma, x \div A)^\ominus$&$:=$&$(\Gamma^\ominus, x \div A)$\\
 $ (\Gamma, h)^\ominus$&$:=$&$\Gamma^\ominus$\\
\end{tabular}\]

\subsection{Rules}

\subsubsection{Context Formation}
\[
\begin{prooftree}
\prov \Gamma \rctx \qquad \Gamma \prov A : \rtype
\justifies
\prov (\Gamma, x : A)\rctx
\end{prooftree}
\]
\[
\begin{prooftree}
\prov \Gamma \rctx \qquad \Gamma^\ominus \prov A : \rtype
\justifies
\prov (\Gamma, x :: A)\rctx
\end{prooftree}
\]
\[
\begin{prooftree}
\prov \Gamma \rctx \qquad \Gamma, h \prov A : \rtype
\justifies
\prov (\Gamma, x \div A)\rctx
\end{prooftree}
\]

\subsubsection{Type Formation}
\[
\begin{prooftree}
\Gamma^\ominus \prov A : \rtype \qquad \Gamma, h \prov M : A
\justifies
\Gamma \prov G_A M : \rtype
\end{prooftree}
\]
\[
\begin{prooftree}
 \Gamma^\oplus \prov  A : \rtype
\justifies
\Gamma \prov  \blat A : \rtype
\end{prooftree}
\]
\[
\begin{prooftree}
 \Gamma, h \prov  A : \rtype
\justifies
\Gamma \prov  \lax A : \rtype
\end{prooftree}
\]
\subsubsection{Term Typing}

\[
\begin{prooftree}
x : A \in  \Gamma
\justifies
\Gamma \prov x : A
\end{prooftree}
\qquad
\begin{prooftree}
x :: A \in  \Gamma
\justifies
\Gamma \prov x : A
\end{prooftree}
\qquad
\begin{prooftree}
x \div A \in  \Gamma \qquad h \in \Gamma
\justifies
\Gamma \prov x : A
\end{prooftree}
\]
\[
\begin{prooftree}
 \Gamma^\ominus \prov M : A
\justifies
\Gamma \prov \{M\}  : G_A M
\end{prooftree}
\qquad
\begin{prooftree}
  \Gamma, h \prov M : A\qquad \Gamma, h \prov N : G_A M
\justifies
\Gamma \prov \pi_M N  : A
\end{prooftree}
\]
\[
\begin{prooftree}
 \Gamma^\oplus \prov M : A
\justifies
\Gamma \prov \iblat M  : \blat A
\end{prooftree}
\qquad
\begin{prooftree}
 \Gamma^\ominus \prov M : \blat A
\justifies
\Gamma \prov \eblat M  : A
\end{prooftree}
\]
\[
\begin{prooftree}
 \Gamma, h \prov M : A
\justifies
\Gamma \prov \ilax M  : \lax A
\end{prooftree}
\qquad
\begin{prooftree}
 \Gamma \prov M : \lax A\qquad h \in \Gamma
\justifies
\Gamma \prov \elax M  : A
\end{prooftree}
\]
\subsection{Weakening}
We let there be a poset on hypotheses and contexts generated by the following:

\begin{itemize}
\item $x :: A \le x : A \le x \div A$
\item $\Gamma, h \le \Gamma$
\item $(x \div A, h) \le (x : A, h)$
\item If $\Gamma \le \Gamma'$ and $\Delta \le \Delta'$ then $\Gamma,\Delta \le \Gamma',\Delta'$.
\end{itemize}

The general weakening theorem is:
\begin{lemma}
If $\Delta \le \Gamma$ and $\Gamma \prov J$, then $\Delta \prov J$.
\end{lemma}

\begin{proof}

\cqed
\end{proof}

\subsection{Computation}


\subsubsection{$G_A M$}
When $h$ is in the context, $\pi_M N$ reduces to $M$. Also:
Also:
\[\pi_M \{ M \} \mapsto_\beta M \qquad N \mapsto_\eta \{ \pi_M N \}\]

To see that $\beta$ is well-typed, stare at
\[
\begin{prooftree}
\Gamma, h \prov M : A
\qquad
\[
 \Gamma^\ominus \prov M :  A
\justifies
 \Gamma, h \prov \{ M\} : G_A M
\]
\justifies
\Gamma \prov  \pi_M \{ M \} : A
\end{prooftree}
\]
and use weakening on $ \Gamma^\ominus \prov M :  A$.

To see that $\eta$ is well-typed, assume
$\Gamma\prov M : A$ and  $\Gamma \prov N : G_A M$,
weaken to
$\Gamma^\ominus, h\prov M : A$ and $ \Gamma^\ominus, h \prov N : G_A M$ and construct
\[
\begin{prooftree}
\[
  \Gamma^\ominus, h \prov M : A\qquad \Gamma^\ominus, h \prov N : G_A M
\justifies
\Gamma^\ominus \prov \pi_M N  : A
\]
\justifies
\Gamma \prov \{\pi_M N\}  : G_A (\pi_M N)
\end{prooftree}
\]
noting that $\pi_M N$ is definitionally equal to $M$ in the context $G_A(\dash)$, which has an $h$.



\subsubsection{$\blat$}
\[\eblat \iblat M \mapsto_\beta M \qquad M \mapsto_\eta \iblat \eblat M\]

To see that $\beta$ is well-typed, stare at
\[
\begin{prooftree}
\[
 \Gamma^{\ominus\oplus} \prov M :  A
\justifies
 \Gamma^{\ominus} \prov \iblat M : \blat A
\]
\justifies
\Gamma \prov  \eblat \iblat M  : A
\end{prooftree}
\]
and use weakening.


To see that $\eta$ is well-typed, assume $\Gamma \prov M : \blat A$,
weaken to
$ \Gamma^{\oplus\ominus} \prov M : \blat A$ and construct
\[
\begin{prooftree}
\[
 \Gamma^{\oplus\ominus} \prov M : \blat A
\justifies
 \Gamma^\oplus \prov \eblat M : A
\]
\justifies
\Gamma \prov \iblat \eblat M  : \blat A
\end{prooftree}
\]

\subsection{Magic Pairing}
\[
\begin{prooftree}
\Gamma, h\prov M : A\qquad  \Gamma^\oplus \prov N : A\qquad
 \Gamma^\oplus, h \prov M \equiv N : A
\justifies
\Gamma \prov \mpair{M}{N}  : A
\end{prooftree}
\]
These maybe compute like so:
\[
\begin{prooftree}
h \in \Gamma
\using \beta_1 \justifies
\Gamma \prov \pair M N \equiv M
\end{prooftree}
\qquad
\begin{prooftree}
 \Gamma\equiv  \Gamma^\oplus
\using \beta_2\justifies
\Gamma \prov \pair M N \equiv N
\end{prooftree}
\qquad
\begin{prooftree}
\Gamma \prov  M : A
\using \eta\justifies
 \pair M M \equiv M
\end{prooftree}
\]
\subsection{Function Type Isomorphism}
I want to define an isomorphism
\[ f : \lax(A \to B) \prov G_{A \to B}(\elax f) \cong (a : \lax A) (a' : G_A(\elax a)) \to G_{B}((\elax f)\ (\elax a))\]

\[ \mathsf{fore} : (f : \lax(A \to B))(f' : G_{A \to B}(\elax f))(a : \lax A) (a' : G_A(\elax a)) \to G_{B}((\elax f)\ (\elax a))\]
\[ \mathsf{fore}\ f\ f'\ a\ a' = \{(\pi f')\ (\pi a')\}\]

We can typecheck $\mathsf{fore}$:

\[
\begin{prooftree}
\[
\[
\cdots, h \prov f' : G_{A \to B}(\elax f)
\justifies
\cdots \prov \pi_{\elax(f)} f' : A \to B
\]
\[
\cdots, h \prov a' : G_{A}(\elax a)
\justifies
\cdots \prov \pi_{\elax(a)} a' : A
\]
\justifies
f\div, f'\div, a\div, a'\div \prov (\pi_{\elax(f)} f')\ (\pi_{\elax(a)} a') : B
\]
\justifies
f, f', a, a' \prov \{(\pi_{\elax(f)} f')\ (\pi_{\elax(a)} a')\} : G_{B}((\elax f)\ (\elax a))
\end{prooftree}
\]
noting that the argument to $G_{A \to B}$ has an $h$ in it, so we can reduce the $\pi$s to their subscripts.

\[ \mathsf{back} : (f : \lax(A \to B)) (k : (a : \lax A) (a' : G_A(\elax a)) \to G_{B}((\elax f)\ (\elax a))) \to  G_{A \to B}(\elax f)\]
\[ \mathsf{back}\ f\ k = \{ \lambda \bar a . \mpair{(\elax f)\ \bar a}{\pi(k\ (\ilax \bar a)\ \{\bar a\})}\} \]

We can typecheck $\mathsf{back}$:
\[
\begin{prooftree}
\[
\[
\[
\[
\justifies
\cdots, h  \prov   \elax f : A \to B
\]
\justifies
\cdots, h  \prov   {(\elax f)\ \bar a} : B
\]
\[
\[
\cdots, h \prov   \{\bar a\} :  G_A(\elax \ilax \bar a)
\justifies
\cdots, h  \prov   k\ (\ilax \bar a)\ \{\bar a\} : G_{B}((\elax f)\ (\elax \ilax \bar a))
\]
\justifies
\cdots, \bar a :: A  \prov   {\pi_{(\elax f)\  \bar a}{(k\ (\ilax \bar a)\ \{\bar a\})}} : B
\]
\qquad
\cdots, \bar a :: A, h \prov (\elax f)\  \bar a \equiv \pi_{(\elax f)\  \bar a} \cdots
\justifies
f \div \cdots, k \div \cdots, \bar a : A  \prov   \mpair{(\elax f)\ \bar a}{\pi_{(\elax f)\  \bar a} (k\ (\ilax \bar a)\ \{\bar a\})} : B
\]
\justifies
f \div \cdots, k \div \cdots \prov  \lambda \bar a . \mpair{(\elax f)\ \bar a}{\pi(k\ (\ilax \bar a)\ \{\bar a\})} : A \to B
\]
\justifies
f : \cdots, k : \cdots \prov \{ \lambda \bar a . \mpair{(\elax f)\ \bar a}{\pi(k\ (\ilax \bar a)\ \{\bar a\})}\}  :   G_{A \to B}(\elax f)
\end{prooftree}
\]
noting that the argument to $G_{A \to B}$ has an $h$ in it, so we can reduce:
\[\lambda \bar a . \mpair{(\elax f)\ \bar a}{\pi(k\ (\ilax \bar a)\ \{\bar a\})} \mapsto \lambda \bar a . {(\elax f)\ \bar a} \equiv \elax f\]


Let's check the roundtrips.

\[\mathsf{fore}\ f\ (\mathsf{back}\ f\ k)\ a\ a'\]
\[ = \{(\pi_{\elax(f)} (\mathsf{back}\ f\ k))\ (\pi_{\elax(a)} a')\} \]
\[= \{((\lambda \bar a . \mpair{(\elax f)\ \bar a}{\pi(k\ (\ilax \bar a)\ \{\bar a\})})\ (\pi_{\elax(a)} a')\} \]
\[= \{\mpair{(\elax f)\ \bar a}{\pi(k\ (\ilax (\pi_{\elax(a)} a'))\ \{\pi_{\elax(a)} a'\})}\} \]
inside $G$-introduction we have a flat context, so we can take the second component of the magic pair:
\[= \{{\pi(k\ (\ilax (\pi_{\elax(a)} a'))\ \{\pi_{\elax(a)} a'\})} \} \]
\[= k\ (\ilax (\pi_{\elax(a)} a'))\ \{\pi_{\elax(a)} a'\} \]
\[= k\ (\ilax (\pi_{\elax(a)} a'))\ a' \]
inside the $\ilax$ we have $h$, so the $\pi$ reduces:
\[= k\ (\ilax \elax a)\ a' \]
\[= k\ a\ a' \]
so \[(\mathsf{fore}\ f) \o (\mathsf{back}\ f)\] is the identity. Let's check the converse:

\[\mathsf{back}\ f\ (\lambda a \ a'. \mathsf{fore}\ f\ f'\ a\ a')\]
\[= \{ \lambda \bar a . \mpair{(\elax f)\ \bar a}{\pi(\mathsf{fore}\ f\ f'\ (\ilax \bar a)\ \{\bar a\})}\}\]
\[= \{ \lambda \bar a . \mpair{(\elax f)\ \bar a}{\pi \{(\pi f')\ (\pi  \{\bar a\})\}  }\}\]
\[= \{ \lambda \bar a . \mpair{(\elax f)\ \bar a}{\pi \{(\pi f')\  \bar a\}  }\}\]
\[= \{ \lambda \bar a . \mpair{(\elax f)\ \bar a}{(\pi f')\  \bar a  }\}\]
Superficially, this seems stuck, but I think because $\bar a$ doesn't need to be strong where it's used, I can
commute the $\lambda$ and the magic pairing:
\[= \{  \mpair{\lambda \bar a .(\elax f)\ \bar a}{\lambda \bar a .(\pi f')\  \bar a  }\}\]
this lets me take the second component
\[= \{  {\lambda \bar a .(\pi f')\  \bar a  }\} = \{  {\pi f'  }\} = f' \]
\subsection{Universe Isomorphism}
I want to define an isomorphism

\[ A :  \lax \rtype \prov G_{\rtype}(\elax A) \cong  \lax (\elax A \to \rtype )\]

