\subsection{Specializing Magic Pairing?}
I want to revisit the $G$ type former.
\[
\begin{prooftree}
\Gamma^\ominus \prov A : \rtype \qquad \Gamma, h \prov M : A
\justifies
\Gamma \prov G_A M : \rtype
\end{prooftree}
\]
\[
\begin{prooftree}
 \Gamma^\ominus \prov M : A
\justifies
\Gamma \prov \{M\}  : G_A M
\end{prooftree}
\qquad
\begin{prooftree}
\Gamma, h\prov M : A\qquad  \Gamma^\oplus, h \prov N : G_A M
\justifies
\Gamma \prov \mpair{M}{N}  : A
\end{prooftree}
\]


Semantically we say
\[ (G_A M)^* = \sem A (M) \qquad \sem {G_A M}(\_) = 1 \]
\[ (\{M\})^* = \sem M \qquad \sem{\{M\}} = \langle\rangle \]
\[ (\mpair M N)^* = M^* \qquad  \sem {\mpair M N} = N^* \]
and then
\[ \mpair M {\{N\}} \mapsto_\beta N \]
\[ N  \mapsto_\eta \{\mpair M N \}\]
and I guess we still also expect $h$ being in the context to trigger first-component reduction, like
\[ \ilax (\mpair M N) \mapsto_h \ilax M \]

We could write
\[ \mathsf{fore} : (f : \lax(A \to B))(f' : G_{A \to B}(\elax f))(a : \lax A) (a' : G_A(\elax a)) \to G_{B}((\elax f)\ (\elax a))\]
\[ \mathsf{fore}\ f\ f'\ a\ a' = \{\mpair{\elax f} {f'}\ \mpair{\elax a}{a'}\}\]
\[ \mathsf{back} : (f : \lax(A \to B)) (k : (a : \lax A) (a' : G_A(\elax a)) \to G_{B}((\elax f)\ (\elax a))) \to  G_{A \to B}(\elax f)\]
\[ \mathsf{back}\ f\ k = \{ \lambda \bar a . \mpair{(\elax f)\ \bar a}{k\ (\ilax \bar a)\ \{\bar a\}}\} \]


